article.headline: Wildcats find shooting touch after 13-13 first half
article.linkText: No. 20 Villanova breaks slump quicker than Notre Dame
article.story:
PISCATAWAY, N.J. (AP) -- Villanova (No. 18 ESPN/USA Today; No. 20 Associated Press) has a shot at the Big
East tournament title because Notre Dame shot as poorly the
Wildcats in the first half Sunday night.

	   Trish Juhline scored 12 of her 14 points in the second half and
Villanova defeated Notre Dame 50-39 in a quarterfinals that will be
remembered for its 13-13 halftime tie.

	   ''I thought that was some type of Guinness Book of Records first
half,'' Notre Dame coach Muffet McGraw said.

	   ''Like I said before, we're a team that lives and dies on the
perimeter,'' Villanova coach Harry Perretta said. ''When we're
going good, we're very good, and when we're bad, we're really
bad.''

	   The Wildcats were horrible in the opening half, shooting
4-for-24, or 17 percent. However, they made up for it in the second
half, converting 12 of 24 in pulling away.

	   Nicole Druckenmiller added 10 points and Kate Dessart-Mager had
nine as Villanova (23-5) advanced to the semifinal Monday against
Miami (18-11). The seventh-seeded Hurricanes upset Rutgers
77-74 in a game decided on a late technical foul for excessive
timeouts.

	   Jacqueline Batteast had 15 points and Courtney LaVere 12 for
Notre Dame (19-10), which will probably get a bid to the NCAA
Tournament next week. Alicia Ratay, who was averaging 12 points,
was held scoreless on 0-for-5 shooting in 31 minutes.

	   ''It was a bad shooting night,'' said Juhline, who was 1-for-7
in the first half and 4-for-10 in the second. ''But that happens.
We played hard the whole game and made shots down the end.''

	   Villanova took the lead for good on a layup by Juhline with
12:34 to play. The basket ignited a 12-2 run that featured two
3-pointers by Druckenmiller for a 35-26 lead.

	   Notre Dame managed to close to six points several times, the
last at 45-39 on a layup with 1:44 to go by Batteast, who also had
nine rebounds.

	   However, Juhline hit two free throws and the Wildcats were never
threatened.
